𝐋𝐢𝐧𝐮𝐱 𝐜𝐨𝐦𝐦𝐚𝐧𝐝𝐬 :

* 𝙎𝙮𝙨𝙩𝙚𝙢 𝙄𝙣𝙛𝙤𝙧𝙢𝙖𝙩𝙞𝙤𝙣 :
top : shows real time system information, including CPU, memory and process usage
htop : offers additional details such as the user who started the process, the command used to start the process, and the process's start time
df -h : Checks disk space usage 
free -h : shows memory usage, including free, used and swap memory
vmstat : system processes, memory, paging, blockid, traps, and CPU activity
iostat : CPU and I/O statics
date : shows the current date and time
cal : shows the months calender
whoami : who are logged in as

* 𝑭𝒊𝒍𝒆 𝑴𝒂𝒏𝒂𝒈𝒆𝒎𝒆𝒏𝒕 :
sudo : executes a command with superuser privileges
ls :  directory listing
ls -la : list files with details
grep pattern file : searches for a specific pattern within a file
mv myfile.txt /home/user/Documents/ : Move a file to another directory
mv old_filename new_filename : Renaming a file only.
cp source_file target_file : This copies the entire file (not just the content) 
cat source_file > target_file : This overwrites the target_file with the content of source_file
cat source_file >> target_file : To append the content instead of overwriting
mkdir yogesh : creates a directory yogesh 
cd yogesh : change directory to yogesh
cd : change to home directory
pwd : shows current working directory
cat file_name : displays the content of the file
touch file_name : create or update a file

* 𝑷𝒓𝒐𝒄𝒆𝒔𝒔 𝑴𝒂𝒏𝒂𝒈𝒆𝒎𝒆𝒏𝒕 :
ps : To display the current working processes
htop : monitors system processes and provides a user-friendly interface

* 𝐅𝐢𝐥𝐞 𝐏𝐞𝐫𝐦𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐢𝐨𝐧 :
chmod octal file :  Change the permission of file to octal,which can 
be found separately for user,group,world by 
adding,
 • 4-read(r)
 • 2-write(w)
 • 1-execute(x)

* 𝙉𝙚𝙩𝙬𝙤𝙧𝙠 :
wget file : Download file
wget -c file : Continue a stopped download 
ping host : Ping host and output results

* 𝐒𝐡𝐨𝐫𝐭𝐜𝐮𝐭𝐬 :
ctrl+c :  Halts the current command
ctrl+d :  Logout the current session, similar to exit 
ctrl+w : Erases one word in the current line
ctrl+u : Erases the whole line


